Project Explanation: Using Conditional GAN For Facial Recognition EnhancementThis is an academic research project authored by T. Pruthviraj Singh (MITS, Madanapalle), T. Mahima Singh (Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham, Chennai), and Deepak Kumar G (MITS, Madanapalle). It sits at the intersection of deep learning, computer vision, and forensic science — using Conditional Generative Adversarial Networks (CGANs) to transform hand-drawn eyewitness sketches into photo-realistic facial images that can help police identify suspects.Here is a detailed breakdown of every major aspect of the project.🎯 1. The Problem & MotivationTraditional criminal investigations rely heavily on forensic sketch artists who draw a suspect based on an eyewitness's memory. This process has several critical weaknesses:Human subjectivity — sketches depend on the artist's skill and the witness's ability to recall subtle details.Missing lifelike features — skin texture, moles, scars, skin tone, and micro-contours are almost always lost.Feature-matching-only software — most existing law-enforcement tools just measure geometric distances (eye-to-nose, jaw width, etc.) and search a sketch database. They do not synthesize a new photo.Poor public usability — a grayscale pencil sketch is far less recognizable on social media or CCTV cross-referencing than a colored, realistic face.Time-critical investigations — manual sketching is slow, and delays give suspects time to escape.The motivation is therefore to bridge the gap between forensic sketching and digital reconstruction using deep learning, producing a lifelike colored image that can be circulated on social media and news channels for faster identification.🧠 2. Why Conditional GANs (and Not Just GANs)?A standard GAN generates random images from noise — useful, but uncontrolled. If you asked a plain GAN to "generate a face," it would give you any face.A Conditional GAN (CGAN) adds a condition (in this case, the input sketch itself, plus attribute labels). This forces the generator to produce a face that strictly obeys the features of the given sketch — same jawline, same eye placement, same hair pattern — but rendered as a photorealistic color image.This "condition" is exactly what makes CGANs suitable for sketch-to-photo translation instead of random face synthesis.CGAN Sketch-to-Photo Architecture

🏗️ 3. System Architecture in Detail

The system has two neural networks locked in an adversarial game, plus a preprocessing and deployment layer.

🔵 The Generator — Encoder–Decoder Network
- Encoder: Takes the input sketch (256×256) plus conditional information (attributes/labels) and compresses it down into a latent representation — essentially a compact numerical fingerprint of the sketch's structural features.
- Decoder: Takes that latent representation and progressively upsamples it back into a full-color, photo-realistic 256×256 face. This is where textures, skin tones, shading, and lifelike details are synthesized — features that were never explicitly drawn in the sketch.

🟠 The Discriminator — CNN-based Classifier
- A Convolutional Neural Network that inspects both real photographs (from the training set) and fake photos (from the Generator).
- Extracts hierarchical features — edges → shapes → facial parts → global identity — using convolution, normalization, and pooling.
- Outputs a real/fake probability, which becomes the training signal for the Generator.

🔁 The Adversarial Loop
1. Initialization — both networks start with random weights.
2. Forward pass — Generator produces a fake face from the sketch + noise + condition.
3. Evaluation — Discriminator classifies the fake face vs. real face.
4. Backpropagation — gradients flow back through both networks; the Generator learns to fool the Discriminator, and the Discriminator learns to catch fakes more accurately.
5. Repeat over many epochs until the Generator produces images the Discriminator can no longer reliably distinguish from real photos.

📊 4. Data & Preprocessing

Datasets used:
- The Google Sketch dataset as the primary source of sketch–photo pairs.
- A diverse collection of real facial images with varying poses, lighting, occlusions, and image quality — used to make the model robust to real-world conditions.

Preprocessing pipeline:
1. Normalization of pixel values to a standard range for stable training.
2. Resizing every image to 256×256 to match the model's expected input.
3. Data augmentation — random transformations (flip, rotate, brightness shift, etc.) on both sketches and photos to expand dataset variability and prevent overfitting.
4. Conditional attribute integration — attaching class labels and attribute vectors to the training pipeline so the Generator learns what to draw, not just how.
5. Data splitting into training / validation / testing subsets.
6. Natural filename sorting and loading into NumPy arrays for batch processing.

