💻 9. Real-World Application — The Streamlit Web App

The trained model is deployed as an interactive web application built with Streamlit:

- User uploads a sketch (JPG, JPEG, or PNG).
- The app automatically resizes it to 256×256.
- The CGAN Generator runs inference in real time.
- The synthesized photorealistic face is displayed alongside the input sketch for comparison.

This turns the research into a field-usable tool for investigators — no ML expertise required by the end user.

🔮 10. Conclusions & Future Work

Conclusions
- CGANs significantly outperform traditional feature-matching approaches for forensic sketch translation.
- The encoder–decoder Generator + CNN Discriminator + dual optimizer (Adam + SGD) design successfully synthesizes structurally faithful, texture-rich color faces.
- Real-time deployment via Streamlit makes the pipeline practical for real investigations.
- The paper also touches on secure cloud-based data sharing (encryption + access control) for collaborative forensic environments.

Future Work
- Ethical framework for using AI-generated faces as forensic evidence — extremely important given the risk of wrongful identification.
- Continuous monitoring for adversarial robustness and emerging security threats.
- Stronger cloud-security measures for handling sensitive suspect data.

🧭 Overall Assessment

This project is a solid application of conditional generative modeling to a socially impactful forensic problem. Its main strengths are:

- ✅ Clear real-world use case with tangible benefit to law enforcement
- ✅ Correct architectural choice (CGAN > vanilla GAN for this task)
- ✅ End-to-end pipeline — from data preprocessing all the way to a deployed Streamlit app
- ✅ Dual-loss evaluation (pixel + structural) is more rigorous than pixel-only

Areas where the paper could be stronger:

- ⚠️ No published numerical L2-norm / SSIM scores or quantitative comparisons against baseline models
- ⚠️ Hyperparameters (epoch count, batch size, learning rate values) are not disclosed
- ⚠️ Ethical implications — especially the risk of hallucinated features leading to wrongful arrests — are acknowledged but not deeply analyzed
- ⚠️ The exact loss-function formulas (e.g., cGAN loss, L1 vs. L2 pixel loss) are not written out

